<br>
Fact: There is only so much loot to go around.<br>
<br>
Therefore:<br>
<br>
Corollary: To reward player A's efforts with extra loot, you need to penalize player B.<br>
<br>
The player that raids a lot already has a bigger chance to win nice loot than the casual raider, simply from his being THERE helping to kill the mobs that drop nice items.  Why should we need to reward him any more than that?<br>
<br>
That's the concept behind the lack of a point system among several guilds (Scions of Veeshan among them).<br>
<br>
Point system aren't about being fair.  They're about ensuring that he who can play the most often (and who raids the most as a consequence) gets extra goodies.  Nevermind that to give an extra to Peter you have to take it from Paul first.<br>
<br>
Faireness, my furry ass.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<br>
This being said, there still are circumstances where a point system is appropriate:<br>
<br>
A point system works well enough for a group of players that are as often online as one another, of the same general level, playing at the same timezone.  LoS comes to mind as an example of this.<br>
<br>
Then, one can say &quot;you all have the same opportunity to contribute to the guild goals, and therefore your rewards will depend on your contribution&quot;.<br>
<br>
The point system also works well when the main goal of the guild is to get ph4t l3wt for its members.  Then one can say &quot;This guild exists to  get uber items.  If you can't play often enough to help us as much as we'd like, then you're not performing and you're in the wrong guild anyways, so don't complain&quot;.<br>
<br>
Life isn't fair, and neither is EQ.  Obtaining uber stuff takes uber effort and commitment, and if you can't afford it, then you have little right to ask for the uber loot.  It's tough, but it's reality.  It's a valid way of running a guild, just not suited to every player.<br>
<br>
When a guild is more casual (like VG or Scions of Veeshan for example), the members are often not in a position to participate as often as they would wish.  So what do we do?  Should we favor the frequent-raiders over the rest of the members?   We chose not to.  <br>
<br>
SoV doesn't use a point system, we simply random the drops among the raiders that are present at the time of the drop, and that can and will use the item.  That means not for a twink, not for selling, not to keep in bank in case it's needed later.  When no one wants something, then everyone on the raid can roll for it, and do with it as they see fit.<br>
<br>
The more you raid, the better the chances that you'll win something.  We believe that should be sufficient, without needing to add incentives.<br>
<br>
No system is perfect, but this one seems to work for us.<br>
